"n.差使；差事 【英】 n. 差使(a trip to do a definite thing ) 【记】 err(跑)+and→跑的事 情→差使 【同】 参考：aberration(跑 偏，越轨) 【例】 I've got a few errands to do in the town. n. 差事(一项特殊任务, 为他人走的一段路, 叫做跑腿) 【记】err徘徊, 跑－跑腿 【参】aberration(n 失常) 【记】er + ran run 跑，爱跑的，结尾attend 出门，参加个会 【相关】random 胡乱，任意，偶然的路线，过程 errand (n.)  Old English ærende ""message, mission; answer, news, tidings,"" from Proto-Germanic *ærundjam (cognates: Old Saxon arundi, Old Norse erendi, Danish ærende, Swedish ärende, Old Frisian erende, Old High German arunti ""message""). Originally of important missions; meaning ""short, simple journey and task"" is attested by 1640s. Related: Errands."
